--- title: "Chapter 2: HRMPA" author: "RWW" date: "2022-09-28" categories: [news] --- 1. Create a character vector called my_names that contains all your first, middle and last names as elements. Calculate the length of my_names. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} my_names <- c("Robert","Wayne","Walker") length(my_names) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 3 ``` ::: ::: 2. Create a second numeric vector called `which` which corresponds to my_names. The entries should be the position of each name in the order of your full name. Verify that it has the same length as my_names. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} which <- c(1,2,3) length(which) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 3 ``` ::: ::: 3. Create a dataframe called names, which consists of the two vectors my_names and which as columns. Calculate the dimensions of names. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} names <- data.frame(my_names,which) dim(names) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 3 2 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} # str(names) ``` ::: *3 rows and 2 columns* 4. Create a new dataframe new_names with the which column converted to character type. Verify that your command worked using str(). ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} new_names <- data.frame(my_names, as.character(which)) str(new_names) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 'data.frame': 3 obs. of 2 variables: $ my_names : chr "Robert" "Wayne" "Walker" $ as.character.which.: chr "1" "2" "3" ``` ::: ::: 5. Load the ugtests data set via the `peopleanalyticsdata` package or download it from the internet.
